            <p>Sumter&#44; So. Ca. 29<hi rend="sup">th</hi> March 1888.<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd. S. Morais<lb/>
                President&#44; Ministers Board Hebrew Seminary Asso.<lb/>
                546 North 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St Philadelphia&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr De Sola Mendes writes to me that<lb/> provision was made&#44; at the recent convention&#44; for<lb/> needy theological students&#44; at the Hebrew Seminary&#44;<lb/> and suggests that I write to you for particulars.<lb/></p>
            <p>You may remember that I wrote to you<lb/> some months ago in relation to my son&#44; Abraham<lb/> Haim Moise&#44; who desires to become an orthodox<lb/> Jewish minister.  He is about 14 years old&#44;<lb/> in good health&#44; has good morals and capacity&#44; and<lb/> has voluntarily expressed a desire to become a<lb/> Jewish clergyman.  Living in this small<lb/> country town&#44; he has had no opportunity to be<lb/> come a Hebrew scholar&#59; but has been trained<lb/> in the ways of orthodox Judaism&#59; and has<lb/> seen in his own family an example of compli<lb/>ance with the requisites of Judaism&#44; in the<lb/> face of wide&#45;spread violations and reckless<lb/> living around us.<lb/></p>
            <p>He was for over a year a<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Cadet at the State Military Academy&#44; as a beneficiary&#59;<lb/> but I was obliged to remove him&#44; because the bigotry<lb/> of the managers&#44; would not permit him to observe<lb/> his sabbath &#40;<hi rend="underline">the only real sabbath</hi>&#41; in the same<lb/> manner in which the Christian pupils observed<lb/> theirs.  I cannot say much for his educational<lb/> progress at that&#44; much vaunted&#44; institution&#59; as I<lb/> found that too much time and attention were<lb/> bestowed upon drilling and mathematics&#44; and<lb/> not enough upon other&#44; and as I think&#44; more<lb/> essential branches.<lb/></p>
            <p>The main thing is his desire to<lb/> follow the ministry as a profession&#59; and<lb/> that is so rare among our native<lb/> youth that I think it ought to be encouraged.<lb/></p>
            <p>Being&#44; as I wrote you&#44; wholly un&#45;<lb/>able to educate him&#44; even in part&#44; at my own<lb/> expense&#44; I submit his case to your kind<lb/> consideration&#44; trusting that you will be<lb/> able to find some way in which his and<lb/> my wishes may be accomplished.<lb/></p>
            <p>Very Respectfully<lb/>
                Ch&#91;&#63;&#93; H Mo&#239;se<lb/></p>
            </body>
